@flexiarg process-coherence/status-refresh-before-work
@title Refresh the Status Against Reality Before Working the Mission
@sigils [⟳/§]
@keywords stale status, mission banner, arming condition, dependency-following, resume, in-progress, starting point, re-derive
@audience any agent (or selector) taking up a mission that has history
@tone procedural
@style pattern

! conclusion: When taking on a mission in progress, do not trust its status banner: re-derive the true status from the document BODY and its cross-referenced dependencies, then UPDATE the status line so work begins at a sensible point in the process. The banner is a cache; the body and the neighbors are the truth.

  + context: Missions accumulate in-body rulings, revised arming conditions, and cross-referenced
    work that lands elsewhere. The status line is written once and goes stale silently while the
    context evolves around it.

  + IF:
      You are taking on a mission in progress (as driver, reviewer, or portfolio-level selector).

  + HOWEVER:
      Its status is out of date relative to the evolving context — arming conditions were revised
      deeper in the body; prerequisites named there have since been satisfied by work in other
      missions; the banner still gates on a condition that no longer exists.

  + THEN:
      Before any other work: read the body past the banner; chase each dependency the current
      phase names to its own current state; re-derive what phase the mission is REALLY at; and
      update the status line to match, citing what you checked. Begin work from the re-derived
      point, not the cached one.

  + BECAUSE:
      A stale banner misdirects everyone downstream of it — agents start at the wrong step, and
      selectors re-choose the mission forever without discovering its next move is already
      unblocked. Minutes of reading beat any amount of machinery pointed at a cached state.
      (Operational kin of `[[futon-theory/honest-map-over-flattering-counter]]` — the banner is a
      map that must be made to match the territory before navigating by it.)

  + canonical-instance:
      M-first-flights, 2026-07-04: banner said Phase B "armed when the rollout engine lands" —
      stale; a ground-control ruling in the body had revised the condition to "terms constructed +
      metric understood", and BOTH had since been satisfied elsewhere (E-mission-mining's 81
      triples; M-substrate-metric's R2 verdict). The WM re-selected this mission across hundreds
      of ticks without discovering Phase B was armed; a direct read found it in minutes
      (E-live-loop-1 origin; distilled same night).
